cmCourseInfo.description: Principles and concepts of evolution and ecology related to origins of adaptation and biodiversity. Mechanisms and processes driving biological diversification illustrated from various perspectives using empirical and theoretical approaches. Topics include: genetic diversity, natural selection, speciation, physiological, population, and community ecology, maintenance of species diversity, conservation, species extinction, global environmental change, and invasion biology. (Lab Materials Fee: $25)
cmCourseInfo.title: Adaptation and Biodiversity
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: Grade 12 Biology or equivalent. Students without high school Biology must consult the BIO120 Office (bio120@utoronto.ca)

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions
Laboratories (practicals) meet in alternate weeks: practical (PRA) meeting sections that end with 1 will take place on the weeks of: Oct. 3, Oct. 17, Oct. 31 and Nov. 14th; PRA meeting sections that end with 2 will take place on the weeks of: Oct. 10, Oct 24, Nov 7 and Nov. 21. Note: On November 8 (when there are no classes), students enrolled in PRA0102 and PRA5102 labs will have their Tuesday, November 8 lab rescheduled to Monday November 14 from 1.30-4.30pm and 6:00-9:00pm respectively; students enrolled in P5102 or P0102 should NOT schedule another course at these times. Tutorials: Optional weekly tutorials are offered M5 and W8, so keep one of these times available. Lab enrolment can be done on ACORN until the evening of Friday September 9; after this lab enrolment and changes can ONLY be made by the BIO120 office. Conflicts: If you plan to take BIO120H1F and CHM135H1F/136H1F labs on the same day in alternating weeks, select PRA sections that end in DIFFERENT digits (example: PRA0201 in BIO120H1F, and PRA0202 in CHM135H1F). You CANNOT alternate labs in BIO120H1F on the same day as labs in CHM151Y1 or PHY131H1F/132H1F/151H1F.

cmCourseInfo.description: One of the goals of modern biology is to understand how the basic building blocks of life give rise to biological form and function. This course provides students with a common lexicon to understand the key principles and concepts in molecular and cell biology, with a focus on how the building blocks of life lead to functioning cells. (Lab Materials Fee: $15).
cmCourseInfo.title: Molecular and Cell Biology
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: SBI4U and SCH4U (Grade 12 University Preparation Biology and Chemistry) or permission of department.  Please contact bio130@utoronto.ca for more information.

Laboratory enrolment can be done on the SWS until Thursday, January 5. cmCourseInfo.description: Dynamics of genetic and ecological change in biological systems, from genomes to ecosystems. Evolutionary genetic and ecological perspectives on wide-ranging topics including disease, aging, sexual conflict, genetics of human differences, conservation, and global climate change. Applications of evolutionary, ecological, and molecular-genetic principles and processes. Responsibilities of human societies in a changing world. (Lab Materials Fee: $25).

cmCourseInfo.description: The genome is the "book of life," providing instructions to construct an organism. This course introduces genome biology and explores how the building blocks of life are networked into functioning organisms. We will investigate how cells perceive internal and external cues, how gene expression is shaped by this perception, and how these events give rise to tissues, organs, and whole organisms. (Lab Materials Fee: $25).
cmCourseInfo.title: From Genes to Organisms
cmCourseInfo.exclusionsText: BIO240H1, BIO241H1, BIO250Y1, BIO255H1, BIO255Y1. Students who have only completed one of BIO240H1 or BIO241H1 can take BIO230H1 for credit.

cmCourseInfo.description: Introduction to structure, function, and ecology of vegetative and reproductive processes in plants with a focus on flowering plants and gymnosperms. Lectures and labs emphasize photosynthesis, respiration, mineral nutrition, transport processes, patterns of plant growth and development, the role of hormones in development, photomorphogenesis, and plant reproduction. (Lab Materials Fee: $25).

courses.name: Cell and Molecular Biology with Advanced Laboratory

cmCourseInfo.description: The genome is the "book of life," providing instructions to construct an organism. This course introduces genome biology and explores how the building blocks of life are networked into functioning organisms. We will investigate how cells perceive internal and external cues, how gene expression is shaped by this perception, and how these events give rise to tissues, organs, and whole organisms.  The Enhanced Laboratory provides the opportunity for greater laboratory skill development in modern investigative techniques and is intended for students interested in conducting their own laboratory research. (Lab Materials Fee: $50).
